// This function finds all root-to-leaf paths in a binary tree using a DFS approach.
The key idea is that we build a string (path) step-by-step as we go down the tree.

TIME COMPLEXITY = O(n)
SPACE COMPLEXITY = O(n)


CODE
class Solution {
public:
     void  path(TreeNode* root , string p , vector<string>&ans){
        if(root == NULL){
            return;
        }
        if(root->left == NULL && root->right == NULL){
            ans.push_back(p);
            return;
        }
        if(root->left){
            path(root->left, p + "->" + to_string(root->left->val) , ans );
        }
        if(root->right){
            path(root->right , p + "->" + to_string(root->right->val) , ans);
        }
     }

 
    vector<string> binaryTreePaths(TreeNode* root) {
     vector<string>ans;
     string p = to_string(root->val);
        path( root , p , ans);
        return ans;

        
    }
};


A MAJOR CONCEPTUAL DOUBT WHILE SOLVING
Since the path is passed by value, each recursive call gets its own copy of the path. 
In other words, changes made in one call do not affect the path in another call. This ensures that after exploring one branch,
we still have the original path intact when we return and explore another branch. 
As a result, we collect all the paths without needing to manually reset anything.
Thus, this approach is efficient and keeps each branch’s exploration independent.
ex - // This function finds all root-to-leaf paths in a binary tree using a DFS approach. The key idea is that we build a
string (path) step-by-step as we go down the tree. Since the path is passed by value, each recursive call has its own copy of
the path. For example, consider a tree like this: 
//       1
//      / \
//     2   3
//      \
//       5
// If we start from node 1, we append '1' to the path. Then we go left: we append '2'. We go left again, but no left child 
exists, so we move right. We append '5'. Thus, the path is "1->2->5". Similarly, we also explore the right subtree from node
1, appending '3'. Each call's path is separate, so after one branch ends, the original path for the parent call stays unchanged.
This ensures that when we backtrack, we still have the right path for other branches.
